{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"686945c3-b062-4cce-9d78-5255fe69b14e","content":"**MSTest.Sdk 4.x dropped the VSTest compatibility layer.** Starting with 4.0.0, the SDK only ships with **Microsoft.Testing.Platform** — the VSTest adapter is no longer included by default, so `vstest.console` can't discover your tests.\n\n### Your options\n\n1. **Switch your CI to `dotnet test`** (recommended) — it uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform natively:\n   ```\n   dotnet test TestProject.csproj\n   ```\n\n2. **Re-enable VSTest compatibility** by adding this to your `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup>\n     <EnableMicrosoftTestingExtensionsCodeCoverage>false</EnableMicrosoftTestingExtensionsCodeCoverage>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n   and referencing the VSTest adapter explicitly:\n   ```xml\n   <ItemGroup>\n     <PackageReference Include=\"MSTest.TestAdapter\" />\n   </ItemGroup>\n   ```\n\n3. **Stay on MSTest.Sdk 3.8.x** if you need `vstest.console` without changes — it still bundles the VSTest adapter.\n\n**Option 1 is the recommended path forward**, as Microsoft.Testing.Platform is the actively developed runner. If your CI calls `vstest.console`, replace that invocation with `dotnet test`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"edd70b9e-9132-43d7-8b9f-f3c184958dae","outputTokens":319,"requestId":"6801:1F16:1B73151:1EF9364:69FD54F4"},"id":"03660b64-0793-489e-b8dd-80a8bb9f1caa","timestamp":"2026-05-08T03:14:04.680Z","parentId":"c1e6d659-58cf-4ac8-a265-3cad55360ddf"}
